Although [https://gentoo.org/get-started/about/ Gentoo is a free operating system based on either Linux or FreeBSD] and FreeBSD has [https://www.freebsd.org/doc/en_US.ISO8859-1/books/handbook/kernelconfig.html its own kernel], for practical reasons, this article refers to the Linux kernel.

<!--T:1-->
The Linux kernel is the core of the operating system and offers an interface for programs to access the hardware. The kernel contains most of the device drivers.

== Installation == <!--T:2-->

=== USE flags === <!--T:39-->

<!--T:40-->
To create a kernel, it is necessary to install the kernel source code first. The Gentoo recommended kernel sources for a desktop system are, of course, {{Package|sys-kernel/gentoo-sources}}. These are maintained by the Gentoo developers, and patched to fix security vulnerabilities, functional problems, as well as to improve compatibility with rare system architectures.

<!--T:41-->
{{USEflag|package=sys-kernel/gentoo-sources}}

=== Emerge === <!--T:42-->

<!--T:43-->
Now install {{Package|sys-kernel/gentoo-sources}}:

<!--T:32-->
{{Emerge|sys-kernel/gentoo-sources}}

== Alternative kernels == <!--T:44--> 

<!--T:7-->
There are various alternative kernel sources in the main Gentoo repository:

<!--T:8-->
* {{Package|sys-kernel/vanilla-sources}} - The official, non-patched Linux kernel sources. These sources are left as is, they do not contain any additional patches and are therefore not supported by Gentoo support or developers.
* {{Package|sys-kernel/hardened-sources}} - Gentoo sources with security enhancements.

=== Sources overview === <!--T:45-->

